b'' b'writes:' b"| (2nd posting of the question that just doesn't seem to get answered)" b'|' b'| suppose you have an idle app with a realized and mapped window that' b'| contains' b'| xlib graphics. a button widget, when pressed, will cause a new item' b'| to be drawn in the window. this action clearly should not call xcopyarea()' b'| (or equiv) directly; instead, it should register the existence of the' b'| new' b'| item in a memory structure and let the same expose event handler that' b'| handles' b'| "regular" expose events (e.g. window manager-driven exposures) take care' b'| of rendering the new image. using an expose event handler is a "proper"' b'| way' b'| to do this because at the time the handler is called, the xlib window is' b'| guaranteed to be mapped.' b'|' b'| the problem, of course, is that no expose event is generated if the window' b'| is already visible and mapped. what we need to do is somehow "tickle" the' b'| window so that the expose handler is hit with arguments that will enable' b'| it to render *just* the part of the window that contains the new item.' b'|' b'| what is the best way to tickle a window to produce this behavior?' b'' b'to incrementally update the contents of windows, i use the following trick:' b'' b'1. set the window background to none,' b'2. call xcleararea(display, window, true),' b'3. restore the window background to its correct value.' b'' b'the call to xcleararea does not repaint the window background, but still' b'generates exposure events for visible parts of the window.' b'' b'in order to let my application know that these expose events must be handled' b'incrementally (something is already displayed on the screen and may need to' b'be erased), i encapsulate the operations with self addressed client' b'messages, which preserve asynchronicity between the client and the server.' b'' b'xgrabserver(display)' b'client message (start-incremental)' b'background none' b'xcleararea' b'restore background' b'client message (end-incremental)' b'xungrabserver(display)' b'' b'the grabserver prevents other events to be inserted by the server in the' b'critical section.' b'' b'---' b'vincent prunet, sema group sophia antipolis' b'inria bp sophia antipolis cedex france' b'' 